<h2 id="Thematic-Role-Systems">Thematic Role Systems<a class="anchor-link" href="#Thematic-Role-Systems">Â¶</a></h2><p><img alt="2019-06-19_19h36_34.png" src="data:image/png;base64, "/></p>
<p><strong>lexical analysis:</strong> each word in to lexical categories; Ashok is a noun, made is a verb
<strong>syntatctic analysis:</strong> structure of sentence; Ashok is a noune phrase, made pan...griddle is a verb phrase etc.
<strong>semantic analysis:</strong> Ashok was agent, made as action, pancakes object etc</p>
<p><strong>semantic</strong> is served by <strong>lexical</strong> and <strong>syntactic</strong></p>
<p><strong>how do we know we understood the meaning?</strong> One could ask related questions, and we could infer right answers.</p>
<p>Note inferences may not be explicit in the sentence. For eg, who ate pancakes? David</p>

</div>
</div>

<h3 id="System">System<a class="anchor-link" href="#System">Â¶</a></h3><ul>
<li>Type of frame system. </li>
<li>An action or event would be identified by a verb (or did he say, just word?)</li>
<li>Example: <strong>Throwing - Who threw? What was thrown?</strong> </li>
<li>Might also expect a target specified by <strong>at</strong>, or destination by <strong>to</strong>. I threw at Ashok or I threw to Ashok.</li>
</ul>

<h2 id="Resolving-Ambiguity-in-Prepositions">Resolving Ambiguity in Prepositions<a class="anchor-link" href="#Resolving-Ambiguity-in-Prepositions">Â¶</a></h2><p><strong>Ontology</strong> tree</p>
<p><img alt="2019-06-19_19h57_25.png" src="data:image/png;base64, "/></p>

</div>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="prompt input_prompt">
</div><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<ul>
<li>Note inferencing David as noun, went as verb, -- this is <strong>bottom up</strong> approach</li>
<li>From constraints, and ontology, we do a <strong>top down</strong> approach - take the "by", know its thematic role, use ontology, etc</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p>So low level or bottom up triggers probes in to memory, which then returns knowledge like ontology, which then can be used for top down approach.</p>
</blockquote>

<h2 id="Ambiguity-in-Verbs">Ambiguity in Verbs<a class="anchor-link" href="#Ambiguity-in-Verbs">Â¶</a></h2><p>1)</p>

<pre><code>I was wondering why ball was getting bigger and it hit me.
    hit is ambiguous
    hit could mean it occurred to me why ball was getting bigger
    hit could mean the ball literally hit me</code></pre>
<p>2) Kleptomanics are those who steal things not for personal or financial gain but by irresistable urge</p>

<pre><code>Its hard to explain puns to kleptomaniacs because they always take things literally
    take is ambiguous
    take could mean, they(kleptomaniacs) interpret the puns in literal sense
    take could also mean, kleptomaniacs steal things literally as a habit</code></pre>

<h3 id="Limitations">Limitations<a class="anchor-link" href="#Limitations">Â¶</a></h3><p>Note how we arrived at inference as "steal"</p>
<p><img alt="2019-06-19_20h25_48.png" src="data:image/png;base64, "/></p>
<p>This was possible because of background knowledge of candy. Think of other sentences..</p>
<ul>
<li>I took the candy <strong>for</strong> the baby</li>
<li>I took a toy <strong>from</strong> the baby</li>
<li>I took the medicine <strong>from</strong> the baby</li>
<li>I took the smile <strong>from</strong> the baby</li>
<li>I took a smile <strong>for</strong> the bay</li>
</ul>
<blockquote><p>More and more variations require more and more rules. Very hard to enumerate all the rules for all variations of sentences</p>
</blockquote>
